  "prompt": "Which digital circuit use by data bus to pass data from memory to register?",
  "response": "In computer architecture, the data bus is a critical component that facilitates the transfer of data between various components such as memory, registers, and the CPU. To efficiently manage these transfers, especially when multiple devices need to access the data bus, **tri-state buffers** are commonly used.\n\n### **Tri-State Buffers Explained**\n\n**Tri-state buffers** are digital electronic components that can exist in one of three states:\n1. **High (1)**\n2. **Low (0)**\n3. **High-impedance (Z)**\n\nThe high-impedance state effectively disconnects the buffer from the bus, allowing other devices to use the data bus without interference. This capability is crucial for preventing data bus conflicts when multiple devices attempt to drive the bus simultaneously.\n\n### **How Tri-State Buffers Facilitate Data Transfer**\n\n1. **Data Output from Memory:**\n   - The memory module outputs data onto the data bus.\n   - A tri-state buffer connected to the memory ensures that the memory can drive the bus only when it's supposed to. When the memory is not active, the buffer goes into the high-impedance state, preventing it from interfering with other devices.\n\n2. **Data Reception by Registers:**\n   - Registers receive data from the data bus.\n   - Another tri-state buffer connected to the register allows the register to capture data from the bus without disrupting other ongoing data transfers.\n\n3. **Bus Control:**\n   - Control logic ensures that only one device (either memory, a register, or another peripheral) is driving the data bus at any given time.\n   - This is managed by enabling the corresponding tri-state buffer for the active device while keeping others in the high-impedance state.\n\n### **Advantages of Using Tri-State Buffers**\n\n- **Bus Sharing:** Multiple devices can share the same data bus without electrical conflicts.\n- **Scalability:** Easily add more devices to the bus by managing their buffer states.\n- **Simplicity:** Simplifies the design of complex systems by managing data flow effectively.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nTri-state buffers are essential in managing data flow on the data bus, ensuring that data can be reliably transferred from memory to registers (and vice versa) without conflicts. Their ability to switch between active and high-impedance states makes them invaluable for maintaining orderly and efficient communication within digital systems.\n\n**Answer:**  \nThey employ tri-state buffer circuits on the data bus to transfer data from memory to registers.",
